1. The Architecture:
"The Brain vs. The Drivers"
In a No-OS server environment, you don't have a kernel to tell you where the network card is or how to write to the NVMe drive. Your library must be designed to receive "Providers" that handle these raw hardware interactions.The Core Library (no_std)This contains the Provisioning Protocol. It handles:Identity: Reading a hardware UUID or MAC address.Security: TLS/mTLS (using a provider like rustls in no_std mode).Policy: "If Disk > 1TB, partition X; else partition Y."The "Standard" Binary (Linux/Windows/BSD)Role: A management agent or a CLI tool.Implementation: Uses standard crates like nix, tokio, and std::fs. It passes standard OS handles into your core library.The "No-OS" Binary (Bare Metal x86_64)Role: A custom "Provisioning Kernel" (Unikernel).Implementation: * Needs a bootloader (like limine or bootloader crate).Must include PCIe enumeration logic to find hardware.Must include Native Drivers (e.g., an virtio-net or e1000 driver for networking).2. Why the Library-First approach is mandatory here If you write this as a single binary, you will struggle to test the No-OS logic. By putting the logic in a library, you can:Fuzz test your provisioning parser on Linux.Unit test your state machine using std mocks.Compile the exact same logic for your UEFI-bootable "Provisioning ISO."3. Implementation BlueprintYou can use Traits to abstract the server hardware. This allows the core library to remain platform-agnostic.InterfaceOS ImplementationNo-OS (Bare Metal) ImplementationNetworkingstd::net::TcpStreamRaw Ethernet frames via a NIC driver + smoltcp.Disk I/Ostd::fs::OpenOptionsBlock-level writes to NVMe/SATA via PCI registers.Loggingprintln! to stdout.Writing to the VGA buffer or Serial COM1 port.Project StructurePlaintext/provisioner-manager
├── Cargo.toml (Workspace)
├── crates/
│   ├── logic-core/      <-- [Library] no_std, logic only.
│   ├── runner-os/       <-- [Binary] The OS agent.
│   └── runner-baremetal/ <-- [Binary] The No-OS "Kernel".
4. Technical Challenges to Watch ForThe "Network Stack" Gap: On a No-OS server, you won't have a TCP/IP stack. You will need to pull in a crate like smoltcp into your No-OS binary to give your library a way to talk to the network.Firmware Interfaces: Your No-OS version will likely need to interact with UEFI Runtime Services to set boot variables (e.g., "Next boot: Boot from local disk").Next StepSince you are targeting No-OS servers, would you like to see the no_std crate dependencies required to handle networking and disk access without an operating system?